🔎 How Vue Works in the Background

Vue is a reactive framework. Its magic is in reactivity + virtual DOM.

1. Reactivity System

Vue wraps your data (ref, reactive) using Proxies.

When you access message.value or user.name, Vue tracks that dependency.

When you change the value, Vue knows which part of the UI depends on it → it schedules a re-render.

👉 This is why updating message.value automatically updates <h1>{{ message }}</h1>.

2. Template Compilation

The HTML template (<h1>{{message}}</h1>) is compiled into a render function.

That render function produces a Virtual DOM tree (a lightweight JS object structure representing the real DOM).

3. Virtual DOM & Diffing

On initial render → Vue builds the Virtual DOM and mounts real DOM.

On updates → Vue builds a new Virtual DOM, compares it with the old one (diffing), and applies minimal changes to the real DOM.

👉 This is why Vue is fast: it doesn’t rebuild the whole page, only updates the changed parts.

4. Lifecycle

Vue components go through setup → mount → update → unmount.

During this, Vue handles dependency tracking and efficient updates.

🖼️ Diagram for Beginners

Here’s a simplified diagram of how Vue works under the hood:

          +------------------+
          |   Your Data      |   (ref, reactive)
          +------------------+
                    |
          (Proxy tracks dependencies)
                    v
          +------------------+
          |   Template       |   ({{ message }}, v-html, etc.)
          +------------------+
                    |
          (Compiled into render function)
                    v
          +------------------+
          | Virtual DOM Tree |
          +------------------+
                    |
          (Diff with old tree)
                    v
          +------------------+
          |   Real DOM       |   (Browser UI updates)
          +------------------+

🔎 What is a Proxy in JavaScript?

A Proxy is a special JavaScript object that lets you intercept and customize operations (like reading, writing, deleting properties) on another object.

Think of it as a “middleman” between your code and the actual object.
Example :
    const user = { name: "Shankar", age: 26 };

const proxyUser = new Proxy(user, {
  get(target, key) {
    console.log(`Accessing ${key}`);
    return target[key];
  },
  set(target, key, value) {
    console.log(`Updating ${key} to ${value}`);
    target[key] = value;
    return true;
  }
});

console.log(proxyUser.name); // Accessing name → Shankar
proxyUser.age = 27;          // Updating age to 27

This is exactly what Vue 3 does internally with reactive() and ref():
    get → Track dependencies (who is reading this value)
    set → Trigger UI updates (who should re-render)

🔎 What does “Compiled into render function” mean?

In Vue (and also React with JSX), your template:

<h1>{{ message }}</h1>


is not executed directly in the browser.
Instead, Vue compiles it into a JavaScript function (called a render function) that returns a Virtual DOM tree.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔎What is ref and reactive 
ref and reactive used for trigger render we can use both of them for primitive and non primitive data type but there is recommend way

    1. ref is used for primitive data type (sting,boolean,number,single value)
        - access value using variableName.value
    2.reactive is used for non primitive (array,object,group of values)
        - access value using variableName

🔎 Diff of ref and reactive
  1.reactive wraps the whole object/array in a Proxy, 
    so mutations like push, pop, property updates are tracked automatically.
    reassigned will not work in reactive

  2.ref tracks only when .value is reassigned; 
    mutations inside .value don’t trigger reactivity unless you use "deep: true" or watch specific properties.

EXAMPLE:
    watch(movies,(newVal,oldVal)=>{
                    if(newVal.length <= 3){
                        setLimit.value = true
                    }else if(newVal.length <= 5 && newVal.length >= 3){
                        setLimit.value = false
                    }
                },{deep:true})
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Directives 
        - Directives are special attributes (start with v-) that extend HTML with Vue’s reactivity.
        - They let Vue control DOM behavior (show, hide, bind, loop, listen to events, etc.).
        - Built-ins: v-bind, v-model, v-if, v-for, v-on, v-show, v-html.
        - You can also create custom directives.

